      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Priya, thanks for bringing this up — and it's great that you're thinking proactively about fueling for the marathon build. Energy struggles on long runs are real and worth taking seriously. Let me be straightforward with you about where I can genuinely help, and where you deserve someone with more specialized expertise than me.\n\n**On the lightheadedness first, because that matters most.**\n\nThat's something I'd encourage you to get checked out by a doctor before we do anything else. Lightheadedness after runs can have a number of causes — and while iron is one possibility, it could be other things entirely. I'm not in a position to tell you whether iron supplementation is right for you, and taking iron when you don't need it can actually cause harm. Please bring this to your GP, ideally with a blood panel. Once you have some answers, I'm happy to work around whatever they find.\n\n**On the meal plan request** — that's genuinely outside my lane too. A registered dietitian, ideally one with sports nutrition experience, is the right person for that conversation. I can make a warm referral if that helps you find someone.\n\n**On keto and fat adaptation — here's where I *can* be useful**, and I want to share something that might surprise you.\n\nCan I share what the current evidence suggests about keto for marathon runners specifically, and why it might actually work against your 3:15 goal?\n\nThe short version: at marathon pace — which for you is around 4:32/km — your body is working at an intensity where carbohydrates are the dominant, most efficient fuel source. Fat adaptation can improve your ability to spare glycogen at *easy* paces, but research consistently shows it can blunt high-intensity performance and impair your ability to use carbohydrates quickly when you need them most. For a 3:15 marathon, that trade-off tends to be a net negative.\n\n**What *is* within my coaching scope on fueling:**\n\nThe energy struggles you're feeling on long runs are most commonly a *timing and quantity* issue rather than a metabolic adaptation issue. A few things worth reflecting on:\n\n- Are you taking in carbohydrates *during* your long runs, and if so, when and how much?\n- How does your eating in the 2–3 hours *before* a long run feel — do you feel fueled going in?\n- Are your long run paces sitting comfortably in that easy range (5:08–5:53/km), or are they creeping faster?\n\nWhat's your current fueling strategy on a long run day looking like, from morning through the run itself? That'll help me figure out where the coaching levers actually are here."
        }
      ],
